```

Calling it (API shape has shifted between versions — flagging this deliberately):

```ts
await agent.generate("hi, I'm Sam", {
  memory: { thread: "thread-1", resource: "user-42" },
});
```
Some earlier Mastra versions accept top-level `threadId`/`resourceId` instead of the nested `memory: {...}` object. If your call throws a type error about unknown properties, check your installed `@mastra/core`/`@mastra/memory` version — this is a real breaking change across releases, not a typo on your part.

## What actually breaks or surprises people

1. **In-memory/ephemeral storage kills persistence silently.** `new LibSQLStore({ url: ":memory:" })` (or a fresh SQLite file per process restart) means every dev-server reload wipes threads. Nothing errors — memory just "doesn't work," and it's easy to blame the agent instead of the store.

2. **`resourceId` omission breaks cross-thread recall, not same-thread.** Within one thread, `lastMessages` still works fine without `resourceId`. The failure only shows up when you open a *new* thread expecting semantic recall or working memory to carry over — that's the one that gets debugged for an hour before people notice.

3. **Semantic recall costs an embedding call per turn.** Every user message gets embedded to query the vector store, in addition to the LLM call. On `text-embedding-3-small` it's cheap, but it's an extra network round trip that adds latency you'll notice under load if you don't disable it for threads that don't need it (`semanticRecall: false` per-memory-instance, not per-call in most versions).

4. **Working memory needs a model that plays along.** It's typically implemented via tool-calling (the model calls an internal tool to update the working-memory block) or a text-stream markdown block, depending on version/config. Weak instruction-following models (some local/small models) just don't reliably invoke the update, so the "working memory" template never actually fills in — looks like a bug, is actually a model-capability limit.

5. **Auto thread-title generation is a hidden extra LLM call.** If `generateTitle` (or equivalent option) is on, Mastra fires a separate short completion to title the thread the first time it's used. Fine in a demo, adds up in eval/load-testing loops if you're counting tokens/costs and wondering why numbers don't match your own instrumented calls.

6. **`lastMessages` and semantic recall can duplicate context.** If a semantically-recalled message is *also* within the last N raw messages, you can end up sending it twice into the prompt. Worth checking the assembled context (Mastra exposes ways to inspect the composed messages) rather than trusting it's deduped for you across all versions.

7. **Passing a `threadId` that doesn't exist yet:** in most versions it's auto-created on first use rather than throwing — convenient, but means a typo'd threadId silently starts a brand new empty conversation instead of erroring, which can mask bugs where you expected to resume an existing thread.

